\smallskip
From relation (\ref{L}) it can be deduced that neither the maximum nor the mean of the lognormal distribution can be considered as an estimation of the landing distance length scale $\mathcal{L}$. 
Further analysis towards a physical parametrisation of fire-spotting is postponed for a future paper,
where firebrand distributions different from the lognormal will be also considered.


















\section{Conclusions}
\label{conclusions}
This paper describes a mathematical formulation to model the effects of random processes into the propagation of the wild-land fires. 
The propagation of the fire can be split into a drifting part and a fluctuating part. 
The drifting part is given by the fire-front position determined from one of the various simulators that exist in literature for 
the propagation of moving interfaces without random phenomena; 
while the fluctuating part is generated by a comprehensive statistical description of the system and includes the effects of random processes 
in agreement with the physical properties of the process. 
The proposed formulation is developed independent of the choice of the method used to ascertain the drifting part and 
serves as a versatile addition to the existing fire spread simulators to include the effects of random spread. 
This fact provides a unique opportunity for the comparison of two simple wildfire simulators based on the Eulerian LSM and on the Lagrangian DEVS scheme.

\smallskip
A series of idealised numerical simulations show that the proposed approach for random effects
emerges to be suitable for both LSM and DEVS based simulators to manage the real world situations related to random character of fire, e.g. 
increase in fire spread due to pre-heating of the fuel by hot air,  vertical lofting and transporting of firebrands, fire overcoming no fuel zones, and development of new isolated secondary fires. 

\smallskip
The simulations from both  LSM and DEVS techniques follow nearly identical patterns, 
and the only difference which distinguishes the outputs from the two techniques is due to the distinction in the treatment of the direction of propagation. 
In DEVS, the active burning points propagate in a direction given by the bisector of the angle made by each marker with its immediate left and right markers, in contrast to the normal direction of propagation used in LSM. Such differences result in ``spurious" flanking fires in DEVS, which 
are anomalous with respect to the definition of the ROS, but qualitatively provide a more ``realistic" representation of the fire contour. Due to this fact, the two methods can be considered complementary to each other for simple situations, but with increasing complexity and the introduction of random processes a validation exercise is necessary to single out the best representation of the fire propagation. 

\smallskip
A brief study on the sensitivity of the firebrand landing distribution to the changes in the shape of the lognormal distribution indicates that 
the modelled firebrands can generate new secondary fires. 
The formulation for the firebrand landing distance can be modified to include information about the wind speed, 
fire intensity, radius of the firebrands and fuel characteristics. 

\smallskip
Though without a validation test case, 
these simulations do provide an insight into the flexibility of this formulation to incorporate 
effects of random processes such as the turbulent heat diffusion and fire-spotting,
specially while characterising the landing distance of firebrands. 
The results from this study provide a support to the implementation of the proposed approach for the effects of random phenomena
into operational softwares such as WRF-SFIRE and ForeFire. The source code utilized for all the simulations in this article is hosted at \url{ https://github.com/forefireAPI/firefront}.

